article.headline: Sonics' Allen shoots 5-for-22
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- The change in the Minnesota Timberwolves over 24 hours was quickly evident to coach Flip Saunders. "Everybody just played more aggressive," Saunders said after the Timberwolves' 104-86 victory over the Seattle SuperSonics on Saturday night. "Tonight, the biggest thing is we weren't hesitant." Kevin Garnett had 28 points and 14 rebounds and Trenton Hassell shut down Ray Allen as the Timberwolves bounced back from a 101-92 loss in Portland Friday night that ended the team's six-game winning streak. Sam Cassell scored 10 of his 20 points in the fourth quarter, Fred Hoiberg scored 14 and Latrell Sprewell added 12 for Minnesota. "Last night all our guys were hesitant," Saunders said. "Tonight, they stayed aggressive and when you stay aggressive, you have a chance to make plays." Rashard Lewis scored 16 points and Allen had 15 but shot just 5-for-22 against Hassell, who has emerged as Minnesota's defensive stopper after being waived by Chicago on Oct. 23. Allen scored 24 points in 23 minutes Tuesday in his first game for Seattle after missing the first 25 games following right ankle surgery Nov. 1. Saunders said Allen, who played 35 minutes, is going to struggle some coming off his seven-week absence. "Hey, listen, we've had guys that have tried to come back off injuries," he said. "It takes time. It takes time to get into the rhythm. He's a great player and he's an explosive player, but once you have an injury and you're coming back, games are rehab." Allen agreed with Saunders' assessment of his game. "I ran up and down the court and I was tired for 30 of those minutes," he said. "I'm not out of the woods yet. There's a lot of basketball I need to play to get in my comfort zone." Minnesota, which had lost its previous five games at Key Arena since its last win in Seattle on Jan. 19, 2001, had a 49-31 rebounding edge. The Timberwolves pulled away in the third quarter, taking a 72-65 lead as Garnett scored 12 points in the period on 4-for-4 shooting. Garnett scored six of his points in the final 3{ minutes, including a 14-footer over Calvin Booth and a 15-footer over Lewis. Cassell, who was acquired by Minnesota in a trade from Milwaukee on June 27, said he's still pinching himself because of the opportunity of getting to play with Garnett. "He's so long and lengthy," Cassell said with a smile. "He wants to be the best player in the court no matter what position he is. That's the thing I like about Kevin Garnett." In the second quarter, the Timberwolves outscored the Sonics 8-2 in the final two minutes, with Hassell making the final two baskets for a 41-38 halftime lead. The Sonics led 19-15 after the first quarter after holding the Timberwolves without a basket for more than five minutes. After leading 11-4 on a 16-footer by Sprewell with 3:02 gone, Minnesota saw the Sonics run off 10 unanswered points before Garnett hit a 19-footer as time expired on the shot clock with 3:14 left in the period. That cut Seattle's lead to 14-13. The Sonics won their first game of the season in Minnesota 89-87 on Nov. 11 in a game in which Ronald Murray scored 29 points for Seattle. Murray had eight points Saturday night. The Timberwolves are communicating better on defense better than they were in November and they were talking about Murray, too, Garnett said. "No disrespect to Flip (Murray), I think he's taken the league by surprise," Garnett said. "When he had a chance, he scored and did things. We were not aware of him then." The Sonics were well aware of what Garnett could do to them -- and they couldn't do anything about it. "He controlled the game on both ends of the floor," Sonics coach Nate McMillan said. "Defensively, he worked his behind off guarding Rashard."

Game notes
PG Brent Barry started for the Sonics after missing three games with a strained left hip flexor. Rookie Luke Ridnour started in Barry's place the previous two games. Barry played for the first time since Dec. 17. "I don't think any player in the league is 100 percent," coach Nate McMillan said. ... With Allen and Barry back in the Sonics' backcourt, McMillan is going to have to make some decisions on playing time. "The one thing I can't do is please everyone," he said. "I'm going to try to put the best combination out there."
